{{italic title}}
[[Image:1907 Cooks Handbook to Norway and Denmark cover.png|thumb|right|''Cook's Handbook to Norway and Denmark'', 1907]]
'''''Cook's Tourists' Handbooks''''' were a series of travel [[guide book]]s for [[tourists]] published in the 19th-20th centuries by [[Thomas Cook & Son]] of London. The firm's founder, [[Thomas Cook]], produced his first handbook to England the 1840s, later expanding to Europe, Near East, North Africa, and beyond. Compared with other guides such as ''[[Murray's Handbooks for Travellers|Murray's]]'', ''Cook's'' aimed at "a broader and less sophisticated middle-class audience."<ref name=koshar1998 /> The books served to advertise Cook's larger business of organizing travel tours.<ref name=koshar1998>{{cite journal |title='What Ought to Be Seen': Tourists' Guidebooks and National Identities in Modern Germany and Europe |author= Rudy Koshar |journal= Journal of Contemporary History |volume= 33 |date=July 1998 |jstor=261119 }}</ref> The series continues today as ''Traveller Guides'' issued by Thomas Cook Publishing of [[Peterborough, England]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Thomas Cook Publishing/Thomas Cook Tour Operations Ltd. |location=Peterborough, England |url= http://www.thomascookpublishing.com/TravellerGuides |title=Traveller Guides |accessdate=26 August 2013 }}</ref>

